[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(28) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "I sent him therefore the more carefully.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—That is, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I was the more earnest and anxious to send him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " In any case the Apostle would have been desirous to express his thanks and send news by Epaphroditus. But the circumstances of his illness increased that desire to greater earnestness.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "I may be the less sorrowful.—There is a peculiar pathos in this expression, as contrasted with the completeness of joy described above in Philippians 2:17-18. Epaphroditus’ recovery and safe return would take away the “sorrow upon sorrow;” but the old sorrow of captivity, enforced inactivity, and anxiety for the condition of the gospel, would remain. The expression of perfect joy belongs to the “spirit which was willing” indeed; the hint of an unspoken sorrow marks the weakness of the flesh.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "I may be the less sorrowful.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—There is a peculiar pathos in this expression, as contrasted with the completeness of joy described above in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Philippians 2:17-18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". Epaphroditus’ recovery and safe return would take away the “sorrow upon sorrow;” but the old sorrow of captivity, enforced inactivity, and anxiety for the condition of the gospel, would remain. The expression of perfect joy belongs to the “spirit which was willing” indeed; the hint of an unspoken sorrow marks the weakness of the flesh.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
